Students Performance: Data Exploration¶

by Youssef Louhaichi¶

Introduction¶

The dataset used in this project is taken from Kaggle and it contains some information about students including their secured marks in a variety of subjects.

Variables:

  • gender: The student's gender
  • race/ethnicity: Race/Ethnicity of the student
  • parental level of education: Level of education of the student's parents
  • lunch: Indicates whether or not the student is having free or reduced lunch
  • test preparation: Indicates whether or not the student has completed a test preparation course
  • math score: The student's math score
  • reading score: The student's reading score
  • writing score: The student's writing score

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 10000 students in the dataset with 8 features:
gender, race/ethnicity,nparental level of education, lunch and test preparation course, are categorical features with parental level of education ordered factor variable with the following levels: some high school, high school, some college, associate's degree, bachelor's degree, master's degree whereas the remaining variables (math score, reading score and writing score) are numeric.

In [23]:
def stacked_bar(data, x, hue, hue_order, ax):
    ''' Quick hack for creating stacked plots '''
    dic={} # Empty dict
    sort = data[x].dtype.ordered == False
    for val in data[x].value_counts(sort=sort).index:
        dic[val]=data.query("{}==@val".format(x)).value_counts(hue)
    # Convert dict to dataframe
    new_df = pd.DataFrame(dic)
    new_df = new_df.rename_axis(None, axis=0)
    new_df = new_df.loc[hue_order] 
    new_df = new_df.apply(lambda x: x/x.sum()) # convert records to percentages
    new_df.transpose().plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax)
    # Rotate xtick labels
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=0)
    import matplotlib.ticker as mtick
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(mtick.PercentFormatter()) #Format y axis as percent
    ax.legend(title=hue)
In [24]:
def category_plot(data, x, hue):
    ''' generate two plots between two gategorical variables '''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,4))
    
    # Setting order for the x_axis variable 
    if data[x].dtype.ordered==False:
        order= data[x].value_counts().index   
    else:
        order=None
    
    # Setting the hue order to use across plots
    hue_order = data[hue].value_counts().index

    # Plot stacked_bar plto at the first axis
    stacked_bar(data, x, hue, hue_order, ax[0])
    
    # Plot countplot at the second axis
    sb.countplot(data=data, x=x, hue=hue, hue_order=hue_order , order=order, ax=ax[1],)
    ax[1].set_ylabel('count')

Now it's time to further our research by looking at multivariate relationships and see if we can spot any interaction effect.

We will start by looking at the relationship between our 3 variables of interest:

In [36]:
def scores_barplots(data, x, hue):
    ''' Bar plots across numeric variables'''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(20,4))
    for i, var in enumerate(numeric_vars):
        sb.barplot(data =df, y=var, x=x, hue=hue, errwidth=0, ax=ax[i]);
        ax[i].get_legend().remove()
    ax[0].legend(loc='lower left', fontsize="small")
In [37]:
scores_barplots(df, 'preparation_course', 'parents_education')

As we previously found, there is a positive correlation between the parental level of education and the students' performance, which was seen through an increase in the average scores with an increasing parental level of education, In this plot, we may notice a steeper increase with students who completed the preparation course.
In order to emphasize the small changes in average score and see if there is truly a difference, a lineplot will be used next

In [38]:
def scores_lineplots(data, x, hue=None):
    ''' Line plots across numeric variables'''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(20,4))
    for i, var in enumerate(numeric_vars):
        sb.lineplot(data =df, y=var, x=x, hue=hue, err_style=None, ax=ax[i], marker='.', markersize=12);
        ax[i].tick_params(axis='x', labelrotation = 20)
In [39]:
scores_lineplots(data=df, x='parents_education', hue='preparation_course')

After adding the preparation course as a third variable, we can notice from the line chart above that the correlation between the parental level of education and scores is slightly stronger for students who have completed the preparation course than those who didn't, which suggest a positive correlation between the preparation course effectiveness and the parental level of education.
